<TITLE> Witnesses give evidence against BDR men </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Panchagar, Apr 4 (bdnews24.com)Prosecution witnesses gave evidence against 29 BDR members accused of mutiny that took place on Feb 25 and 26 2009. The special court of 25 Rifles Battalion on Monday set Tuesday for the accused to give their statements and to hear the prosecutors' arguments. The second phase of the trial of the special court began on Sunday with seven of the accused admitting their involvement with the mutiny. After seven admitted their involvement with the mutiny, charges were pressed against 29 members. On Monday, the 29 witnesses gave evidence for the prosecution, three of whom identified 18 of the accused from video footage. BDR chief Maj Gen Moinul Islam presided over the court, with deputy attorney general Biswajit Roy, Lt Col Mahfuzur Rahman and Maj Didar Al Latif present as the prosecutors. Supreme court lawyers Mosharraf Hossian Kajol and Manzurul Huq were also present to assist the prosecutor. An army officer was also present as a 'friend of the accused' to assist some of the defendents, and three private lawyers were also present. The February 2009 mutiny saw over 70 people brutally killed, nearly 60 of them army officers deputed to the border force. Rebellion also spread to other BDR outposts around the country. The BDR members at Panchagar open fired some hundred rounds and blockaded Dhaka-Panchagar highway. On November 15, the government formed six special courts, including two in Dhaka, to try about 3,500 border guards accused in 40 cases around the country. In the event of a guilty finding, the maximum penalty for rebellion under the BDR Act is seven years in jail. The six special courts are trying charges of mutiny, looting and arson. Allegations of murder will be tried separately in civilian courts. bdne
